{"title_page": "Arthur Wolfe, 1st Viscount Kilwarden", "text_new": "{{Use Irish English|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix   = \n| name               = The Viscount Kilwarden\n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| honorific-suffix   = \n| image              = Portrait of Arthur Wolfe (Viscount Kilwarden) by Hugh Douglas Hamilton.jpg\n| imagesize          = \n| smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Portrait by [[Hugh Douglas Hamilton]]\n| order              = \n| office             = [[Lord Chief Justice of Ireland|Lord Chief Justice of the King's Bench in Ireland]]\n| term_start         = 3 July 1798\n| term_end           = 23 July 1803\n| alongside          = <!--For two or more people serving in the same position from the same district.  (e.g. United States Senators.)-->\n| vicepresident      = \n| viceprimeminister  = \n| deputy             = \n| lieutenant         = \n| monarch            = \n| president          = \n| primeminister      = \n| taoiseach          = \n| chancellor         = \n| governor           = \n| governor-general   = \n| governor_general   = \n| constituency       = \n| majority           = \n| succeeding         = <!--For President-elect or equivalent-->\n| predecessor        = [[John Scott, 1st Earl of Clonmell|Lord Clonmell]]\n| successor          = [[William Downes, 1st Baron Downes|William Downes]]\n| prior_term         =\n\n| order2             =  <!--Can be repeated up to eight times by changing the number-->\n| office2            =  Member of Parliament for [[Dublin City (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Dublin City]]\n| term_start2        =  January 1798\n| term_end2          =  July 1798\n| alongside2         =  [[John Claudius Beresford]]\n| monarch2           =  <!--Can be repeated up to eight times by changing the number-->\n| primeminister2     =  <!--Can be repeated up to eight times by changing the number-->\n| predecessor2       =  [[Lord Henry FitzGerald]]\n| successor2         =  [[George Ogle]]\n\n| birth_date         = 19 January 1739\n| birth_place        = Forenaughts House, [[Naas]], County Kildare, [[Kingdom of Ireland]]\n| death_date         = 23 July 1803 (aged 64)\n| death_place        = [[Dublin]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain & Ireland]]\n| restingplace       = \n| restingplacecoordinates = \n| birthname          = \n| citizenship        = \n| nationality        = \n| party              = \n| otherparty         =  <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n| spouse             = [[Anne Ruxton]]\n| partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations          = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| residence          = \n| alma_mater         = [[Trinity College Dublin]]\n| occupation         = \n| profession         = \n| cabinet            = \n| committees         = \n| portfolio          = \n| religion           = \n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n| website            = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\n'''Arthur Wolfe, 1st Viscount Kilwarden''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KC}} (19 January 1739 \u2013 23 July 1803) was an Irish [[peerage|peer]], politician and judge, who held office as [[Lord Chief Justice of Ireland]]. He was assassinated during the [[Irish rebellion of 1803]].\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Arthur Wolfe, 1st Viscount Kilwarden and his wife Anne by Thomas Hickey.jpg|thumb|Arthur Wolfe, 1st Viscount Kilwarden and his wife Anne ([[Thomas Hickey (painter)|Thomas Hickey]], 1769)]]\n\nArthur Wolfe was born at Forenaughts House, near [[Naas]], being the eighth of nine sons born to John Wolfe (1700\u20131760) and his wife Mary (d. 1763), the only child and heiress of William Philpot, a successful merchant at [[Dublin]]. One of his brothers, Peter, was the [[High Sheriff of Kildare]], and his first cousin Theobald was the father of the poet [[Charles Wolfe]].\n\n==Career==\nWolfe was educated at [[Trinity College Dublin]] - where he was [[List of Scholars of Trinity College Dublin|elected a Scholar]] - and at the [[Middle Temple]] in London. He was called to the Irish Bar in 1766. In 1769, he married [[Anne Wolfe, 1st Baroness Kilwarden|Anne Ruxton]] (1745\u20131804), and after building up a successful practice [[took silk]] in 1778. He and. Anne had four children, John, Arthur, Mariana and Elizabeth.<ref>Debrett's Peerage</ref>\n\nIn 1783, Wolfe was returned as Member of Parliament for [[Coleraine (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Coleraine]], which he represented until 1790. In 1787, he was appointed [[Solicitor-General for Ireland]], and was returned to Parliament for [[Jamestown (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Jamestown]] in 1790.\n\nAppointed [[Attorney-General for Ireland]] in 1789, he was known for his strict adherence to the forms of law, and his opposition to the arbitrary measures taken by the authorities, despite his own position in the [[Protestant Ascendancy]]. He unsuccessfully prosecuted [[William Drennan]] in 1792. In 1795, [[William Fitzwilliam, 4th Earl Fitzwilliam|Lord Fitzwilliam]], the new [[Lord Lieutenant of Ireland|Lord Lieutenant]], intended to remove him from his place as Attorney-General to make way for [[George Ponsonby]]. In compensation, Wolfe's wife was created '''Baroness Kilwarden''' on 30 September 1795; however, the recall of Fitzwilliam enabled Wolfe to retain his office.\n\nIn January 1798, he was simultaneously returned to Parliament for [[Dublin City (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Dublin City]] and [[Ardfert (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Ardfert]]. However, he left the House of Commons when he was appointed [[Chief Justice of the Kings Bench for Ireland]] and created '''Baron Kilwarden''' on 3 July 1798.\n\n===Wolfe Tone===\nAfter the [[Irish Rebellion of 1798]], Kilwarden became notable for  twice issuing  writs of ''[[habeas corpus]]'' on behalf of [[Wolfe Tone]], then held in military custody, but these were ignored by the army and forestalled by Tone's [[suicide]] in prison. In 1795 he had also warned Tone and some of his associates to leave Ireland to avoid prosecution. Tone's godfather, Theobald Wolfe of Blackhall (the father of [[Charles Wolfe (poet)|Charles Wolfe]]) was Kilwarden's first cousin, and Tone may have been Theobald's natural son. These attempts to help a political opponent were unique at the time.\n\nAfter the passage of the [[Act of Union (1800)|Act of Union]], which he supported, Kilwarden was created '''Viscount Kilwarden''' on 29 December 1800. In 1802, he was appointed Chancellor of the [[University of Dublin]].<ref>[http://www.tcd.ie/chancellor/prochancellor/former/ Former Pro-Chancellors \u2013 The Chancellor : Trinity College Dublin, The University of Dublin, Ireland<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nDespite his actions on behalf of Wolfe Tone, Kilwarden was hated by the [[United Irishmen]] for his prosecution of [[William Orr (United Irishman)|William Orr]] in 1797, and he had entertained considerable fear for his safety after their failed rebellion. His murder in 1803 is often said to have been a delayed revenge for the death of Orr. Another theory is that it was a case of mistaken identity, the real target being his colleague [[Hugh Carleton, 1st Viscount Carleton]] (although several witnesses said that Wolfe identified himself to his killers, who replied \"You're the one we want\").\n\nIn 1802 he presided over the case against [[Henry Charles Sirr (soldier)|Major Sirr]] in which the habitual abuses of power used to suppress rebellion were exposed in court.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/trialbynisipriu00bencgoog#page/n9/mode/1up ''Trial of Mr John Hevey, Plaintiff and Charles Henry Sirr, Defendant'', John Stockdale, Dublin, 1802.]. Retrieved 4 February 2013.</ref><ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=IDSHnsyqZ8IC&pg=PA61&lpg=PA61 Niles' weekly register, page 61, Volume 20 By Hezekiah Niles, William Ogden Niles. Retrieved 4 February 2013.</ref>\n\n===Father Gahan===\nIn the same year he ordered that the well-known Catholic priest Father [[William Gahan]] be imprisoned for [[contempt of court]]. In a case over the disputed will of Gahan's friend [[John Butler, 12th Baron Dunboyne]], the priest refused to answer certain questions on the ground that to do so would violate the [[priest-penitent privilege|seal of the confessional]], despite a ruling<ref>''[[Butler v Moore]]'' (1802)</ref>(which was overturned in the twentieth century)<ref>''Cooke v Carroll'' 1945 IR 515</ref> that the common law did not recognize the seal of the confessional as a ground for refusing to give evidence. The judge may well  have felt some personal sympathy for Gahan's predicament, as he was released from prison after only a few days.\n\n==Death==\nDuring the 1803 rebellion, Kilwarden, who had never been forgiven by the United Irishmen for the execution of William Orr, was clearly in great danger.  On the night of 23 July 1803, the approach of the [[Kildare]] rebels induced him to leave his residence, Newlands House, in the suburbs of Dublin, with his daughter Elizabeth<ref>His daughter is referred to in contemporary accounts of the murder simply as Miss Wolfe, which could  mean either Mariana (1777\u20131814) or her younger sister Elizabeth (1778\u20131806), but later sources name her as  Elizabeth.</ref> and his nephew, Rev. Richard Wolfe.<ref>''The Parliamentary Register; Or, History of the Proceedings and Debates of ...,'' Vol III, London, 1804, p 876. https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MXpHAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false(accessed 28 February 2017).</ref>\nThinking that he would be  safer among the crowd, he ordered his driver to proceed by way of Thomas Street in the city centre; however, the street was occupied by [[Robert Emmet]]'s rebels. Unwisely, when challenged, he gave his name and office, and he was rapidly dragged from his carriage and stabbed repeatedly with [[pike (weapon)|pike]]s. His nephew was murdered in a similar fashion, while Elizabeth  was allowed to escape to [[Dublin Castle]], where she raised the alarm.  When the rebels were suppressed, Kilwarden was found to be still living, and was carried to a watch-house, where he died shortly thereafter. His last words, spoken in reply to a soldier who called for the death of his murderers, were \"Murder must be punished; but let no man suffer for my death, but on a fair trial, and by the laws of his country.\"\n\nHe was succeeded by his eldest son [[John Wolfe, 2nd Viscount Kilwarden]].  Neither John nor his younger brother Arthur, who died in 1805, had male issue, and on John's death in 1830 the title became extinct.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*''[[Dictionary of National Biography]]'', Wolfe, Arthur, first Viscount Kilwarden (1739\u20131803), lord chief justice of Ireland, by C. L. Falkiner. Published 1900.\n* {{cite IrishBio|subpage=Wolfe, Arthur, Viscount Kilwarden}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|ie}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Richard Jackson (Coleraine MP)|Richard Jackson]] | before2=[[John Beresford (statesman)|John Beresford]] | title=Member of Parliament for [[Coleraine (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Coleraine]] | with=[[Richard Jackson (Coleraine MP)|Richard Jackson]] | years=1783\u20131790 | after=[[Sir George Jackson, 1st Baronet|George Jackson]] | after2=[[John Beresford (statesman)|John Beresford]]}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Sir Francis Hutchinson, 1st Baronet|Sir Francis Hutchinson]] | before2=[[Henry Bruen (1741\u20131795)|Henry Bruen]] | title=Member of Parliament for [[Jamestown (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Jamestown]] | with=[[Henry Wood (politician)|Henry Wood]] 1790\u20131796 | with2=[[Robert King, 1st Viscount Lorton|Hon. Robert King]] 1796\u20131798 | years=1790\u20131798 | after=[[Sir Gilbert King, 1st Baronet|Gilbert King]] | after2=[[John King (1760\u20131821)|John King]]}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Robert Day (politician)|Robert Day]] | before2=[[Richard Archdall]] | title=Member of Parliament for [[Ardfert (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Ardfert]] | with=[[Robert Day (politician)|Robert Day]] | years=1798 | after=[[Robert Day (politician)|Robert Day]] | after2=[[Charles FitzGerald, 1st Baron Lecale|Lord Charles FitzGerald]]}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Lord Henry FitzGerald]] | before2=[[Henry Grattan]] | title=Member of Parliament for [[Dublin City (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Dublin City]] | with=[[John Claudius Beresford]] | years=1798 | after=[[John Claudius Beresford]] | after2=[[George Ogle]]}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Hugh Carleton, 1st Viscount Carleton|Hugh Carleton]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Solicitor-General for Ireland]] | years=1787\u20131789}}\n{{s-aft | rows=2 | after=[[John Toler, 1st Earl of Norbury|John Toler]]}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[John Fitzgibbon, 1st Earl of Clare|John Fitzgibbon]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Attorney-General for Ireland]] | years=1789\u20131798}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[John Scott, 1st Earl of Clonmell|The Earl of Clonmell]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Lord Chief Justice of the King's Bench in Ireland]] | years=1798\u20131803}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[William Downes, 1st Baron Downes|The Lord Downes]]}}\n{{s-reg|ie}}\n{{s-new | rows=2 | creation}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Viscount Kilwarden]] | years=1800\u20131803}}\n{{s-aft | rows=2 | after=[[John Wolfe, 2nd Viscount Kilwarden|John Wolfe]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Baron Kilwarden]] | years=1798\u20131803}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kilwarden, Arthur Wolfe, 1st Viscount}}\n[[Category:1739 births]]\n[[Category:1803 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Assassinated Irish politicians]]\n[[Category:Attorneys-General for Ireland|Wolfe, Arthur]]\n[[Category:Irish barristers]]\n[[Category:Irish MPs 1783\u20131790|Wolfe, Arthur]]\n[[Category:Irish MPs 1790\u20131797|Wolfe, Arthur]]\n[[Category:Irish MPs 1798\u20131800|Wolfe, Arthur]]\n[[Category:Lords Chief Justice of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Ireland (pre-1801) for County Dublin constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Ireland (pre-1801) for County Kerry constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Ireland (pre-1801) for County Leitrim constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Ireland (pre-1801) for County Londonderry constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Peers of Ireland created by George III]]\n[[Category:Politicians from County Kildare]]\n[[Category:Scholars of Trinity College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Solicitors-General for Ireland|Wolfe, Arthur]]\n[[Category:Viscounts in the Peerage of Ireland]]\n[[Category:19th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:1800s murders in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:19th-century murders in Ireland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Irish English|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix   = \n| name               = The Viscount Kilwarden\n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| honorific-suffix   = \n| image              = Portrait of Arthur Wolfe (Viscount Kilwarden) by Hugh Douglas Hamilton.jpg\n| imagesize          = \n| smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Portrait by [[Hugh Douglas Hamilton]]\n| order              = \n| office             = [[Lord Chief Justice of Ireland|Lord Chief Justice of the King's Bench in Ireland]]\n| term_start         = 3 July 1798\n| term_end           = 23 July 1803\n| alongside          = <!--For two or more people serving in the same position from the same district.  (e.g. United States Senators.)-->\n| vicepresident      = \n| viceprimeminister  = \n| deputy             = \n| lieutenant         = \n| monarch            = \n| president          = \n| primeminister      = \n| taoiseach          = \n| chancellor         = \n| governor           = \n| governor-general   = \n| governor_general   = \n| constituency       = \n| majority           = \n| succeeding         = <!--For President-elect or equivalent-->\n| predecessor        = [[John Scott, 1st Earl of Clonmell|Lord Clonmell]]\n| successor          = [[William Downes, 1st Baron Downes|William Downes]]\n| prior_term         =\n\n| order2             =  <!--Can be repeated up to eight times by changing the number-->\n| office2            =  Member of Parliament for [[Dublin City (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Dublin City]]\n| term_start2        =  January 1798\n| term_end2          =  July 1798\n| alongside2         =  [[John Claudius Beresford]]\n| monarch2           =  <!--Can be repeated up to eight times by changing the number-->\n| primeminister2     =  <!--Can be repeated up to eight times by changing the number-->\n| predecessor2       =  [[Lord Henry FitzGerald]]\n| successor2         =  [[George Ogle]]\n\n| birth_date         = 19 January 1739\n| birth_place        = Forenaughts House, [[Naas]], County Kildare, [[Kingdom of Ireland]]\n| death_date         = 23 July 1803 (aged 64)\n| death_place        = [[Dublin]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain & Ireland]]\n| restingplace       = \n| restingplacecoordinates = \n| birthname          = \n| citizenship        = \n| nationality        = \n| party              = \n| otherparty         =  <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n| spouse             = [[Anne Ruxton]]\n| partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations          = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| residence          = \n| alma_mater         = [[Trinity College Dublin]]\n| occupation         = \n| profession         = \n| cabinet            = \n| committees         = \n| portfolio          = \n| religion           = \n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n| website            = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\n'''Arthur Wolfe, 1st Viscount Kilwarden''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KC}} (19 January 1739 \u2013 23 July 1803) was an Irish [[peerage|peer]], politician and judge, who held office as [[Lord Chief Justice of Ireland]]. He was assassinated during the [[Irish rebellion of 1803]].\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Arthur Wolfe, 1st Viscount Kilwarden and his wife Anne by Thomas Hickey.jpg|thumb|Arthur Wolfe, 1st Viscount Kilwarden and his wife Anne ([[Thomas Hickey (painter)|Thomas Hickey]], 1769)]]\n\nArthur Wolfe was born at Forenaughts House, near [[Naas]], being the eighth of nine sons born to John Wolfe (1700\u20131760) and his wife Mary (d.1763), the only child and heiress of William Philpot, a successful merchant at [[Dublin]]. One of his brothers, Peter, was the [[High Sheriff of Kildare]], and his first cousin Theobald was the father of the poet [[Charles Wolfe]].\n\n==Career==\nWolfe was educated at [[Trinity College Dublin]] - where he was [[List of Scholars of Trinity College Dublin|elected a Scholar]] - and at the [[Middle Temple]] in London. He was called to the Irish Bar in 1766. In 1769, he married [[Anne Wolfe, 1st Baroness Kilwarden|Anne Ruxton]] (1745\u20131804), and after building up a successful practice [[took silk]] in 1778. He and. Anne had four children, John, Arthur, Mariana and Elizabeth.<ref>Debrett's Peerage</ref>\n\nIn 1783, Wolfe was returned as Member of Parliament for [[Coleraine (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Coleraine]], which he represented until 1790. In 1787, he was appointed [[Solicitor-General for Ireland]], and was returned to Parliament for [[Jamestown (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Jamestown]] in 1790.\n\nAppointed [[Attorney-General for Ireland]] in 1789, he was known for his strict adherence to the forms of law, and his opposition to the arbitrary measures taken by the authorities, despite his own position in the [[Protestant Ascendancy]]. He unsuccessfully prosecuted [[William Drennan]] in 1792. In 1795, [[William Fitzwilliam, 4th Earl Fitzwilliam|Lord Fitzwilliam]], the new [[Lord Lieutenant of Ireland|Lord Lieutenant]], intended to remove him from his place as Attorney-General to make way for [[George Ponsonby]]. In compensation, Wolfe's wife was created '''Baroness Kilwarden''' on 30 September 1795; however, the recall of Fitzwilliam enabled Wolfe to retain his office.\n\nIn January 1798, he was simultaneously returned to Parliament for [[Dublin City (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Dublin City]] and [[Ardfert (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Ardfert]]. However, he left the House of Commons when he was appointed [[Chief Justice of the Kings Bench for Ireland]] and created '''Baron Kilwarden''' on 3 July 1798.\n\n===Wolfe Tone===\nAfter the [[Irish Rebellion of 1798]], Kilwarden became notable for  twice issuing  writs of ''[[habeas corpus]]'' on behalf of [[Wolfe Tone]], then held in military custody, but these were ignored by the army and forestalled by Tone's [[suicide]] in prison. In 1795 he had also warned Tone and some of his associates to leave Ireland to avoid prosecution. Tone's godfather, Theobald Wolfe of Blackhall (the father of [[Charles Wolfe (poet)|Charles Wolfe]]) was Kilwarden's first cousin, and Tone may have been Theobald's natural son. These attempts to help a political opponent were unique at the time.\n\nAfter the passage of the [[Act of Union (1800)|Act of Union]], which he supported, Kilwarden was created '''Viscount Kilwarden''' on 29 December 1800. In 1802, he was appointed Chancellor of the [[University of Dublin]].<ref>[http://www.tcd.ie/chancellor/prochancellor/former/ Former Pro-Chancellors \u2013 The Chancellor : Trinity College Dublin, The University of Dublin, Ireland<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nDespite his actions on behalf of Wolfe Tone, Kilwarden was hated by the [[United Irishmen]] for his prosecution of [[William Orr (United Irishman)|William Orr]] in 1797, and he had entertained considerable fear for his safety after their failed rebellion. His murder in 1803 is often said to have been a delayed revenge for the death of Orr. Another theory is that it was a case of mistaken identity, the real target being his colleague [[Hugh Carleton, 1st Viscount Carleton]] (although several witnesses said that Wolfe identified himself to his killers, who replied \"You're the one we want\").\n\nIn 1802 he presided over the case against [[Henry Charles Sirr (soldier)|Major Sirr]] in which the habitual abuses of power used to suppress rebellion were exposed in court.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/trialbynisipriu00bencgoog#page/n9/mode/1up ''Trial of Mr John Hevey, Plaintiff and Charles Henry Sirr, Defendant'', John Stockdale, Dublin, 1802.]. Retrieved 4 February 2013.</ref><ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=IDSHnsyqZ8IC&pg=PA61&lpg=PA61 Niles' weekly register, page 61, Volume 20 By Hezekiah Niles, William Ogden Niles. Retrieved 4 February 2013.</ref>\n\n===Father Gahan===\nIn the same year he ordered that the well-known Catholic priest Father [[William Gahan]] be imprisoned for [[contempt of court]]. In a case over the disputed will of Gahan's friend [[John Butler, 12th Baron Dunboyne]], the priest refused to answer certain questions on the ground that to do so would violate the [[priest-penitent privilege|seal of the confessional]], despite a ruling<ref>''[[Butler v Moore]]'' (1802)</ref>(which was overturned in the twentieth century)<ref>''Cooke v Carroll'' 1945 IR 515</ref> that the common law did not recognize the seal of the confessional as a ground for refusing to give evidence. The judge may well  have felt some personal sympathy for Gahan's predicament, as he was released from prison after only a few days.\n\n==Death==\nDuring the 1803 rebellion, Kilwarden, who had never been forgiven by the United Irishmen for the execution of William Orr, was clearly in great danger.  On the night of 23 July 1803, the approach of the [[Kildare]] rebels induced him to leave his residence, Newlands House, in the suburbs of Dublin, with his daughter Elizabeth<ref>His daughter is referred to in contemporary accounts of the murder simply as Miss Wolfe, which could  mean either Mariana (1777\u20131814) or her younger sister Elizabeth (1778\u20131806), but later sources name her as  Elizabeth.</ref> and his nephew, Rev. Richard Wolfe.<ref>''The Parliamentary Register; Or, History of the Proceedings and Debates of ...,'' Vol III, London, 1804, p 876. https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MXpHAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false(accessed 28 February 2017).</ref>\nThinking that he would be  safer among the crowd, he ordered his driver to proceed by way of Thomas Street in the city centre; however, the street was occupied by [[Robert Emmet]]'s rebels. Unwisely, when challenged, he gave his name and office, and he was rapidly dragged from his carriage and stabbed repeatedly with [[pike (weapon)|pike]]s. His nephew was murdered in a similar fashion, while Elizabeth  was allowed to escape to [[Dublin Castle]], where she raised the alarm.  When the rebels were suppressed, Kilwarden was found to be still living, and was carried to a watch-house, where he died shortly thereafter. His last words, spoken in reply to a soldier who called for the death of his murderers, were \"Murder must be punished; but let no man suffer for my death, but on a fair trial, and by the laws of his country.\"\n\nHe was succeeded by his eldest son [[John Wolfe, 2nd Viscount Kilwarden]].  Neither John nor his younger brother Arthur, who died in 1805, had male issue, and on John's death in 1830 the title became extinct.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*''[[Dictionary of National Biography]]'', Wolfe, Arthur, first Viscount Kilwarden (1739\u20131803), lord chief justice of Ireland, by C. L. Falkiner. Published 1900.\n* {{cite IrishBio|subpage=Wolfe, Arthur, Viscount Kilwarden}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|ie}}\n{{succession bo