{"title_page": "List of Midwestern urban areas", "text_new": "Urbanized areas in the [[United States]] are defined by the [[United States Census Bureau|U.S. Census Bureau]] as contiguous census block groups with a [[population density]] of at least 1,000 per square mile (about 400 per square km). Urban areas are delineated without regard to political boundaries. Urban areas with a population of at least 50,000 serve as the core of a [[metropolitan statistical area]].<ref>[https://www.census.gov/geo/www/ua/ua_2k.html Census 2010 Urban and Rural Classification.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014182213/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/ua/ua_2k.html |date=2013-10-14 }} United States Census Bureau. Accessed October 16, 2016.</ref>\n\n==Areas over 100,000==\nThe following is a list of [[urbanized area]]s in the [[United States|American]] [[Midwest]] with a population of at least 100,000. States within the Midwest are [[Illinois]], [[Indiana]], [[Iowa]], [[Kansas]], [[Michigan]], [[Minnesota]], [[Missouri]], [[Nebraska]], [[North Dakota]], [[Ohio]], [[South Dakota]] and [[Wisconsin]].  Areas are ranked based on population as listed in the 2010 [[United States Census, 2010|U.S. Census]].\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" | style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!Rank\n!Urbanized Area\n!Population<br><small>(2010 census)</small><ref name=\"List of UAs\">[https://www.census.gov/geo/www/ua/ua2k.txt Alphabetically sorted list of Urbanized Areas.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020613030345/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/ua/ua2k.txt |date=2002-06-13 }}  U.S. Census Bureau.  Accessed October 16, 2016.</ref>\n|-\n| 1\n| align=\"left\" | [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]], IL-IN-WI\n| 8,608,208\n|-\n| 2\n| align=\"left\" | [[Detroit]], MI\n| 3,737,090\n|-\n| 3\n| align=\"left\" | [[Minneapolis, Minnesota|Minneapolis]]-[[Saint Paul, Minnesota|St. Paul]], MN-WI\n| 2,650,890\n|-\n| 4\n| align=\"left\" | [[Saint Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]], MO-I