{"title_page": "Phil Harvey (manager)", "text_new": "{{BLP refimprove|date=July 2014}}\n'''Philip Christopher Hammond Harvey''' (born 29 August 1976) is the manager of the band [[Coldplay]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clientearth.org/people/trustees/phil-harvey |title=Environmental lawyers &#124; Phil Harvey |publisher=ClientEarth |accessdate=2014-07-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726060843/http://www.clientearth.org/people/trustees/phil-harvey |archivedate=July 26, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Phil Harvey\n| known_for     = Coldplay\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1976|8|28|mf=y}}\n| education     = {{unbulleted list |[[Sherborne School]], \n[[Trinity College, Oxford]]}}\n\n}}\n\nHarvey attended [[Sherborne School]] alongside [[Chris Martin]] from 1990 to 1995, where he was the second academic scholar in his year group; he then proceeded to study [[Classics]] at [[Trinity College, Oxford]].\n\n==Association with Coldplay==\nWhen, in 1998, Martin complained to Harvey about the vice-like grip one of the [[Camden Town|Camden]] promoters had on the band, he suggested that they put on their own event at [[Dingwalls]] in Camden. It was here that they managed to sell the first fifty copies of the [[Safety EP|''Safety'' EP]], which Phil himself had helped fund along with his father (Christopher Harvey) and his Oxford roommate.<ref name=\"coldplay.com\">{{cite web|title=We Interview Coldplay's Manager|url=http://www.coldplay.com/ezine/ezine1.pdf |accessdate=March 30, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071111124731/http://www.coldplay.com/ezine/ezine1.pdf |archivedate=November 11, 2007 }}</ref> It is generally considered that this was when he could first be described as the band's manager.\n\nHarvey eventually dropped out of his [[University of Oxford|Oxford University]] studies to manage the band; he carried out the role more or less single-handedly until early 2001 when the stress of performing a role usually requiring a team of people forced him to take a prolonged break. He has since stated that the 2001 [[Brit Awards]] was his lowest point:\n\n<blockquote>\nI was feeling like death when I should have been on top of the world. The band picked up awards for Best British Band and Album and all I could think about was how much I wanted to be in bed. It was two days later that my doctor phoned to say she was worried I might be about to slip into a coma.<ref name=\"coldplay.com\"/>\n</blockquote>\n\nAlthough Dave Holmes has now taken over as Coldplay's manager, Phil Harvey is still heavily involved in the band's creative output. He was also cited as the band's fifth member, for example in the liner notes for ''[[A Rush of Blood to the Head]]'', ''[[Viva la Vida or Death and All His Friends]]'', ''[[Prospekt's March]]'', ''[[Ghost Stories (Coldplay album)|Ghost Stories]]'' and ''[[A Head Full of Dreams]]''. This band membership was stressed by Coldplay in a direct appeal to [[Wikipedia]] on their site in 2008, pleading fans and \"Wikipedia Enthusiasts\" to rectify a few errors on their [[Coldplay|page]]. They stated that ''\"(...)Coldplay officially have five members - with the mysterious Mr. Phil Harvey making up the quintet.\"''<ref name=\"id=80\">{{cite web|url=http://www.coldplay.com/newsdetail.php?id=80|title=Newsreel: An appeal to Wikipedia enthusiasts|website=coldplay.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809171008/http://www.coldplay.com/newsdetail.php?id=80|archive-date=2017-08-09|url-status=dead|accessdate=7 May 2016}}</ref> On Coldplay's [[Myspace]] and [[Facebook]] pages, he was described as \"The wise, handsome, frightening one who tells us what to do.\"<ref name=\"myspace\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/13/magazine/13wwln-medium-t.html |title=Coldpage |work=[[The New York Times]] |first=Virginia |last=Heffernan |date=23 July 2008 |accessdate=14 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Facebook\">{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/coldplay/info |title=Coldplay - Info |publisher=[[Facebook]] |accessdate=14 November 2013}}</ref> Harvey has also made cameo appearances in four Coldplay music videos. His first appearance was in \"[[Life in Technicolor II]]\" as one of the men carrying a video camera, and his second appearance was in \"[[Christmas Lights (song)|Christmas Lights]]\" as one of the [[Elvis]]es. He also played in the video for \"[[Paradise (Coldplay song)|Paradise]]\" as one of two zookeepers chasing after the runaway elephant, and features in a koala suit in the band's video for \"[[A Sky Full of Stars]]\".\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.coldplay.com/}}\n\n{{Coldplay}}\n{{Grammy Award for Record of the Year 2000s}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harvey, Phil}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Sherborne School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Coldplay members]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP refimprove|date=July 2014}}\n'''Philip Christopher Hammond Harvey''' (born 29 August 1976) is the manager of the band [[Coldplay]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clientearth.org/people/trustees/phil-harvey |title=Environmental lawyers &#124; Phil Harvey |publisher=ClientEarth |accessdate=2014-07-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726060843/http://www.clientearth.org/people/trustees/phil-harvey |archivedate=July 26, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nHarvey attended [[Sherborne School]] alongside [[Chris Martin]] from 1990 to 1995, where he was the second academic scholar in his year group; he then proceeded to study [[Classics]] at [[Trinity College, Oxford]].\n\n==Association with Coldplay==\nWhen, in 1998, Martin complained to Harvey about the vice-like grip one of the [[Camden Town|Camden]] promoters had on the band, he suggested that they put on their own event at [[Dingwalls]] in Camden. It was here that they managed to sell the first fifty copies of the [[Safety EP|''Safety'' EP]], which Phil himself had helped fund along with his father (Christopher Harvey) and his Oxford roommate.<ref name=\"coldplay.com\">{{cite web|title=We Interview Coldplay's Manager|url=http://www.coldplay.com/ezine/ezine1.pdf |accessdate=March 30, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071111124731/http://www.coldplay.com/ezine/ezine1.pdf |archivedate=November 11, 2007 }}</ref> It is generally considered that this was when he could first be described as the band's manager.\n\nHarvey eventually dropped out of his [[University of Oxford|Oxford University]] studies to manage the band; he carried out the role more or less single-handedly until early 2001, when the stress of performing a role usually requiring a team of people forced him to take a prolonged break. He has since stated that the 2001 [[Brit Awards]] was his lowest point:\n\n<blockquote>\nI was feeling like death when I should have been on top of the world. The band picked up awards for Best British Band and Album and all I could think about was how much I wanted to be in bed. It was two days later that my doctor phoned to say she was worried I might be about to slip into a coma.<ref name=\"coldplay.com\"/>\n</blockquote>\n\nAlthough Dave Holmes has now taken over as Coldplay's manager, Phil Harvey is still heavily involved in the band's creative output. He was also cited as the band's fifth member, for example in the liner notes for ''[[A Rush of Blood to the Head]]'', ''[[Viva la Vida or Death and All His Friends]]'', ''[[Prospekt's March]]'', ''[[Ghost Stories (Coldplay album)|Ghost Stories]]'' and ''[[A Head Full of Dreams]]''. This band membership was stressed by Coldplay in a direct appeal to [[Wikipedia]] on their site in 2008, pleading fans and \"Wikipedia Enthusiasts\" to rectify a few errors on their [[Coldplay|page]]. They stated that ''\"(...)Coldplay officially have five members - with the mysterious Mr Phil Harvey making up the quintet.\"''<ref name=\"id=80\">{{cite web|url=http://www.coldplay.com/newsdetail.php?id=80|title=Newsreel: An appeal to Wikipedia enthusiasts|website=coldplay.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809171008/http://www.coldplay.com/newsdetail.php?id=80|archive-date=2017-08-09|url-status=dead|accessdate=7 May 2016}}</ref> On Coldplay's [[Myspace]] and [[Facebook]] pages, he was described as \"The wise, handsome, frightening one who tells us what to do.\"<ref name=\"myspace\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/13/magazine/13wwln-medium-t.html |title=Coldpage |work=[[The New York Times]] |first=Virginia |last=Heffernan |date=23 July 2008 |accessdate=14 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"facebook\">{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/coldplay/info |title=Coldplay - Info |publisher=[[Facebook]] |accessdate=14 November 2013}}</ref> Harvey has also made cameo appearances in four Coldplay music videos. His first appearance was in \"[[Life in Technicolor II]]\" as one of the men carrying a video camera, and his second appearance was in \"[[Christmas Lights (song)|Christmas Lights]]\" as one of the [[Elvis]]es. He also played in the video for \"[[Paradise (Coldplay song)|Paradise]]\" as one of two zoo keepers chasing after the runaway elephant, and features in a koala suit in the band's video for \"[[A Sky Full of Stars]]\".\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.coldplay.com/}}\n\n{{Coldplay}}\n{{Grammy Award for Record of the Year 2000s}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harvey, Phil}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Sherborne School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Coldplay members]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Anaitaallen", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phil_Harvey_(manager)"}
